#chapter(12, "Secret conversations of not-so-silent upperclassmen")[
  "Uta-sama, thank you, SO, SO MUCH." Mikoto clasped her hand.

  "Uhm- thank you too!" Mona continued, expressing her gratitude to her friend.

  Mikoto and Mona was thanking Uta as if she was a god. Mikoto even went as far
  as to kneel down to her friend.

  "You two really are... Especially Mikoto! You were the one orchestrating this
  entire event, yet you can't even handle something so simple!" Uta pointed her
  finger at Mikoto, "I'm going home."

  // from her second place FC
  "No, don't! Uta-sama, my benevolent queen, please don't be petty! I'm sorry,
  okay? Please, go with us to one more club, alright? Mona wanted to check out
  the clubs with you too! Right, Mona?"
  Mikoto threw out everything from her arsenal at once in an attempt to convince
  her friend, yet to no avail. Even Mona, a dear new friend of hers, was not
  spared from her desperation.

  "Uhm, yes, I do!"

  With this, Mona finally picked Mikoto's side. Though, it was not like she had
  a choice, since saying no would mean the _did_ mind visiting clubs with Uta's
  presence, which could not be further from the truth.

  "Well, it's not like I have a choice, wasn't it?" Uta playfully remarked.
  Following that, Mikoto's expression immediately brighten up.

  "Thank you so much, Uta!" Mikoto repeated her motions from earlier, with Mona
  now joining in as well.

  "Though, I think we do need a short break." Uta remarked.

  "Agreed."

  Mikoto, after everything that ensued, came to the window to feel the breeze
  for a brief moment. She leaned towards the window, letting her ponytail cutely
  swayed in the wind.

  Her hair wiggled. Left to right, right to left. Mikoto let out a satisfied
  expression on her face. Even Mona, standing a little farther
  from five meters from her friend, could see the wind was gentle today, as
  well.

  After enjoying the chilling wind for a bit, the girl let out a honest thought,

  "But, Koto-senpai is truly a nice person."

  "Yeah, much nicer than YOU."

  Uta replied to Mikoto with a personal attack, which Mikoto was at no position to
  resist. Seeing how there was still a lot of space left, Uta would then also
  come to enjoy the wind, pulling her phone out to kill time while Mikoto was
  resting comfortably.

  Mona was left alone, yet again. She looked at the remaining space, seemingly
  enough for another girl, but honestly she did not want to come. She stood, as
  if frozen, by the classroom door. All she wanted now was to recharge her
  social battery, which had reached a new low today.

  Noticing her friend standing still, Mikoto broke the silence,

  "Hey, Mona! Come here if you are tired too!"

  "Heh? I’m okay." Mona reluctantly shook her head, "Just staying here is fine."

  The spring breeze is nice for her, but honestly she did not want to join in
  with the two. Laziness? Awkwardness? Or maybe a mix of the two?
  "It would be nice to be there, but I am fine here", something like that.

  "Don’t be like that. The chilling spring breeze is really relaxing."

  Mikoto then let out a soft hum. She seemed to be enjoying herself. Even Uta,
  who were expressionless at times, was wearing a slightly blissful look right
  now.

  Because of Mikoto's persistence, Mona now had no choice other than to come to
  the window frames with the other two. _"It really feels great here..."_, she
  thought, but honestly this pleasant alone would not be able to move her feet,
  if Mikoto did not invite her to come over.

  Meanwhile, in the clubroom that they were just left from...

  "Do you seriously think they will come here again?" A voice broke the silence,
  sourcing from the seat right next to Koto.

  "Ako, it's not nice to say that! It’s not their faults for being uninterested
  in our hobbies, you know?"

  Tsukishima Ako, the owner of the honorary Second Prize that Koto just told
  the three girls about, put down the dense text she had been focusing on
  earlier. She took a moment to adjust her shoulder-length, dark brown hair,
  which had been messed up by quite a bit without noticing, as she was deeply
  invested in her novel for quite some time now.

  _You, me and the helicopter noises_. It was a novel setting place in
  post-World-War-2 Japan, where the protagonist and her lover was separated due
  to the intragenerational split at the time. She was intending to write about
  this topic for her next novel, but she felt in love with the characters. Even
  though she knew a sad ending was inevitable, she could not help but root for
  both of them.

  "I'm just being realistic here. You should just chase them away or something,
  what a waste of time."

  Koto put down her text and sighed.

  "You don’t get it, do you? These girls are so cute, I just want to keep them
  here forever! It's a shame that they left so early..." She grinned, in a
  slightly creepy yet playful tone.

  // diddy yamal
  "Okay, keep glazing younger girls like that, and you'll be the main character
  of the monthly pedo exposed drama." Ako pulled up her phone, "Are you going to
  invite dwarves to your birthday party next?"

  "I have not stooped to that level! Anyway, did we have a thing or two about
  using slangs in the clubroom? You are ruining the mood for everyone else."
  Koto spoke in a serious yet mischievous voice, "Anyone felt disturbed by Ako,
  please raise your hand!"

  Koto then raised her hand, and the other club members promptly followed. Their
  focus remained stuck like glue to their reading material, and their approval
  to Koto felt like a ceremonial thing. Yet, those still counted as valid votes.

  They were not paying much attention to the conversation, yet they knew what
  was probably happening. The club's noisy president and vice-president, though
  rarely speaking up loud, was arguing on a stupid topic yet again. Them raising
  their hands were just a way for them to put oil into a fire, escalating the
  already pointless bickering.

  "It's just the natural process of language evolution like it has been for
  thousands of years, y'know. Stop being so old-fashioned." Ako showed an
  article on her smartphone right at Koto's face, "100 years ago, the language
  that we are currently using is generally frown upon and considered as slangs!"

  The screen was so close to Koto's face that she could barely make out the
  title. Out of reflex, she pulled her head backward. It was only then that she
  could skim the rest of the web page. It looked like it came from a credible
  source, yet sloppily written.

  "Ako, why don't you end your sentences with skibidi toilet if you like changes
  that much? It's the language of the next generation after us, right?"

  The other giggled. Not because of Koto's funny joke, but rather the fact that
  seeing her saying "skibidi toilet" was definitely not on their bingo card for
  this year. And maybe even next year too.

  Koto sighed. Ever since her friend picked up a conversation with her, she
  could not focus on her reading. She was also at a good part, too. What a
  waste.

  Koto and Ako, being the inseparable president-vice-president duo of the club,
  frequently had banters like these. They had been close since elementary
  school. The other members were perfectly okay with
  them, and they even said so. The members who were sensitive to noises generally
  did not attend club to focus on their readings, so breaking the silent yet
  suffocating atmosphere once in a while is completely fine for the two girls.

  // watashi sacchan ga daisuki da...
  Unlike Koto who liked to see the flustered expressions of her juniors, Ako's
  sole interest was just Koto. She "loved" her friend to the point of studying
  hard just to go to the same high school as her, joining the Classical
  Literature club despite not knowing jack about the subject just to end up in the
  same club with her, and, always sitting next to her in the clubroom.

  There was once a time when a new girl accidentally took the seat next to Koto,
  and after that one afternoon, _mysteriously_ disappeared from the club,
  leaving only a resignation form with her name. The perpetrator was still
  unknown, but some club members were pretty sure, say 99\%, with their suspections.
  Koto was still in the dark, nonetheless. Honestly she would be freaked out if
  she did.

  // Having medium-length black hair and a bright face, the girl seemed to be a
  // much more playful and mischievous version of her friend. She also was teasing
  // Koto because, according to her, "people shines the most when they're having
  // // the model is narumi sena btw
  // banters with friends", quoted from a famous model on TV.

  // Koto seemed to not notice the strangeness of her friend, however. She would be
  // freaked out if she did, anyway.

  Though, to be fair, Ako had been a great help to Koto throughout their shared
  childhood. Koto had been not quite good with handling people, so it was lucky
  for her to have Ako handle all the hard work of socializing. After everything
  ended up being done and well, Koto would always be in awe of her friend, while
  still being clueless about Ako's real intention.

  "Anyway, was that the Narumi Mona girl that I've been hearing about recently?
  She was much shyer than I expected from the little sister of Narumi Sena."
  Koto questioned.

  "Right, that has to be her. I think. The blonde shade on her hair is just like
  Sena-san's. See?" Ako showed Koto a picture of Narumi Sena, taken straight
  from her Mitter page.

  "If that's Sena-san then I have to agree..." Koto pondered, while staring at
  Sena's most distinct features, "But not gonna lie, she's so cute! Maybe not as
  much as her sister, but it feels like a different flavor, y'know!"

  Koto would then illustrated her point using an analogy around chocolate and
  matcha latte ice cream. This was not the first time she had drawn such
  comparisons, either.

  Ako sighed. She could put up with her friend's antics anymore.

  "Anyone grossed out by this pedo, please raise your hand!" Ako announced in a
  fed-up tone filled with frustration.

  Yet, no one raised their hands. It was as if no one had said anything.

  "Hey! Are you kidding? This girl is being freaky as heck and no one cares? Do
  you really think of our club's reputation? What if she's blabbering things like
  this in an award ceremony? And when I say just a word of what? skibidi toilet?
  And you all went to bully me?" She screamed out loudly.

  Still, no one budged their heads, still immersed in their own readings. And
  the soundproofing of the room went both ways, so even people in the hall would
  be unaware to her fury.

  "Just give up, Ako. No one is going to be on your side." Koto giggled, before
  bursting into a laugh, unable to contain herself.

  "Shut up, you freak! How much did you pay everyone!"

  "Ako-chan, you shouldn't throw such _baseless accusations_ to an innocent girl
  like me..." Koto shrugged, "I treat everyone with utmost care and respect,
  well maybe I treated some ice cream for the scholarship thing... Anyway, what
  are we talking about... Ah! Narumi Mona-chan. She is so cute, right?"

  "Right, right, Mona-chan. Very cute. Okay? Wait, what do you mean 'treated
  some ice cream'? You treated everyone except ME?"

  "No-no-no I can explain! See, it was just a coincidence!" Koto flustered, "I,
  well, just met them by chance in an ice cream shop and decided to thank them
  for their help!"

  "Yet you don't give anything to the one who helped you the most?" Ako stared
  with judgmental eyes.

  "I will make up for you later, okay?" Koto clasped her hand, slightly bowing
  to her friend.

  "Haizz~, I'm going back to my book, this is so tiring."

  Ako sighed for the umpteenth time.

